"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-lifestyle-celeb-news-local-celebs-rachel-kolisi-celebrates-sister-in-law-tatjana-smith-paris-olympics-joel\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bb'A South African gem': Rachel Kolisi celebrates sister-in-law Tatjana  Rachel Kolisi celebrated her sister-in-law Tatjana Smith after she returned from making South African history at the Paris Olympics 2024.  Rachel Kolisi, the wife of Springboks skipper Siya Kolisi, took to Instagram to celebrate her sister-in-law, Tatajana Smith, who made South African history at the Paris Olympics 2024.  Tatjana Smith made history at the Paris Olympics 2024. She is greatest-achieving Olympian after bagging her fourth Olympic medal. Tatjana is married to Rachel Kolisi's brother, Joel Smith. The pair tied the knot in November 2023.  The proud sister-in-law took to Instagram to show some love. Rachel expressed that Tatjana is a South African gem and she is so proud. Take a look\\u2026  \\\"I can not believe she's my sister-in-law \\ud83e\\udd79.  A South African gem, I am so proud of you\\u00a0@tatjanaschoen\\u00a0for the medals yes, but mostly for the sacrifices, hard decisions, and commitment to our good Lord. \\u2764\\ufe0f,\\\" she wrote.  \\\"Spent the day with our\\u00a0@mercedesbenzsa\\u00a0and\\u00a0@kolisi_foundation\\u00a0fam today doing a power 2 you activation with a group of high school girls. (This meant we could sneak in a lunch with Tats and\\u00a0@jcsmith7\\u00a0). A beautiful day in JHB with beautiful people \\ud83d\\ude4f\\ud83c\\udffc,\\\" she continued.  A post shared by Rachel Kolisi (@rachelkolisi)  Here'ssix things to know about Tatjana.Take a look atsix things to know about the athlete's career.  The Olympic medalist called time on her careerafter her last race at the Paris Olympics 2024 on Thursday 1 August. Tatjana expressed that she is looking forward to a life outside of swimming.  \\\"I am looking forward to my life outside of swimming. It was an amazing battle and I have never raced Kate (Douglass) in an Olympic final before. I could not have asked for a better way to end my career in a very tough battle. I have always loved competing,\\\" she said.  She went on to say that achievements fall away and people are remembered for who they are and bringing joy.  \\\"Achievements fall away. You are remembered for who you are and I want to be remembered for bringing people joy. Swimming is a part of a season in your life and now I am excited to live life,\\\" she said confirming her retirement.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or by emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.comor sending a WhatsApp to\\u00a0060 011 021 1  You can also follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor the latest news.  'The South African' is hiring! Freelance writer positions available. Send us your CV  The draw for Rugby World Cup 2027 will take place in Sydney, Australia on Wednesday, 3 December at 11:00 (SA time).  Today's Daily Lotto jackpot stands at an estimated R550 000. If you want to win your share of the jackpot, you have to play!  Faberge's The Winter Egg, fetched a record \\u00a322.9 million (R518 million) at auction on Tuesday, Christie's said.  Former Pirates star Phumudzo Manenzhe has discussed the exclusion of Thapelo Morena from Bafana Bafana's AFCON 2025 squad.  Kaizer Chiefs will play their penultimate match of 2025 on Wednesday, 3 December when they visit Chippa United in Gqeberha.  Secures a NEW shopping bag? Woolworths has seemingly disassociated itself with the testimony of 'tenderpreneur' Vusi 'Cat Matlala\\u2026    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted with